item_prototype.name: $1: average queue size
item_prototype.description: The average queue length of the requests that were issued to the device.

item_prototype.name: $1: average requests size
item_prototype.description: The average size (in sectors) of the requests that were issued to the device.

item_prototype.name: $1: await
item_prototype.description: The average time (in milliseconds) for I/O requests issued to the device to be served. This includes the time spent by the requests in queue and the time spent servicing them.

item_prototype.name: $1: read from device per second
item_prototype.description: The number of kbytes read from the device per second

item_prototype.name: $1: read requests merge per second
item_prototype.description: The number of read requests merged per second that were queued to the hard disk

item_prototype.name: $1: read operations per second
item_prototype.description: The number of read requests per second

item_prototype.name: $1: Average disk operations time
item_prototype.description: Average executing time of disk operations

item_prototype.name: $1: utilization
item_prototype.description: Percentage of CPU time during which I/O requests were issued to the device (bandwidth utilization for the device). Device saturation occurs when this value is close to 100%.

item_prototype.name: $1: written to the device per second
item_prototype.description: The number of kilobytes written to the device per second.

item_prototype.name: $1: write requests merge per second
item_prototype.description: The number of write requests merged per second that were queued to the device.

item_prototype.name: $1: write operations per second
item_prototype.description: The number (after merges) of write requests completed per second for the device.

trigger.name: Elasticsearch Cluster in {ITEM.LASTVALUE} state
trigger.description: The cluster health status is: green, yellow or red. On the shard level, a red status indicates that the specific shard is not allocated in the cluster, yellow means that the primary shard is allocated but replicas are not, and green means that all shards are allocated. The index level status is controlled by the worst shard status. The cluster status is controlled by the worst index status.

The index level status is controlled by the worst shard status. The cluster status is controlled by the worst index status.
